[[File:Yin yang.svg|thumb|160px|right|The [[taijitu|yin yang symbol]] which illustrates opposites together.]]
'''Enantiosis''', '''synoeciosis''' or '''discordia concors''' is a [[rhetorical device]] in which opposites are juxtaposed so that the contrast between them is striking.<ref>{{citation |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=_kd_nBXJ3hAC&pg=PA184 |title=Estudis de llengua, literatura i cultura catalanes |author=J.W.Marchand |chapter=Acyrologia in the poems of Ausia March}}</ref>  Examples include the famous maxim of [[Augustus]], ''[[festina lente]]'' (hasten slowly),<ref>{{citation |author=Desiderius Erasmus, William Watson Barker |title=The adages of Erasmus |isbn=0-8020-4874-9 |publisher=University of Toronto Press |date=2001 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VmJn6IFMyicC |page=132 |chapter=Festina lente}}</ref> and the following passage from [[Second Epistle to the Corinthians|Paul's second letter to the Corinthians]]:<ref>{{citation |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=EPKUzUwwg70C&pg=PA247 |title=Rhetoric |author=Thomas Gibbons |chapter=The ENANTIOSIS considered |year=1767}}</ref>{{cquote|By honour and dishonour, by evil report and good report: as deceivers, and yet true;<br>As unknown, and yet well known; as dying, and, behold, we live; as chastened, and not killed;<br>As sorrowful, yet alway rejoicing; as poor, yet making many rich; as having nothing, and yet possessing all things.}}

Dr. [[Samuel Johnson|Johnson]] in his ''[[Lives of the Most Eminent English Poets|Lives of the Poets]]'' (1779) defined discordia concors as "a combination of dissimilar images, or discovery of occult resemblances in things apparently unlike. (...) The most heterogeneous ideas are yoked by violence together." 
